    </ul>

    <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Requires electricity — not suitable for locations without power</li>
      <li>Higher maintenance than manual (motor servicing, belt replacement)</li>
      <li>Heavier and less portable than manual crushers</li>
      <li>Three-phase models may require electrical upgrades</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Ideal for:</strong> Commercial sugarcane juice stalls, market setups, mall kiosks, juice bars, and any business serving 100–500+ glasses per day.</p>

    <h3>3. Automatic Sugarcane Juice Machine (with Extraction + Filtering)</h3>
    <p>The automatic sugarcane juice machine is the most advanced option available. These machines not only crush the cane but also include built-in filtering systems (mesh or centrifugal) that deliver clean, fibre-free juice directly into a dispensing container. Some premium models also include cooling systems to keep the juice chilled.</p>

    <p><strong>Key specifications:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Motor power:</strong> 2 HP to 5 HP</li>
      <li><strong>Roller material:</strong> SS 304 grade (food-safe) with hardened alloy rollers</li>
      <li><strong>Number of rollers:</strong> 3 or 4 rollers with integrated filter mesh</li>
      <li><strong>Extraction efficiency:</strong> 85–92% juice extraction</li>
      <li><strong>Output:</strong> 200–500+ glasses per hour</li>
      <li><strong>Additional features:</strong> Auto-reverse, overload protection, drip tray, built-in filter, some with cooling tank</li>
      <li><strong>Power requirement:</strong> Three-phase electric</li>
      <li><strong>Weight:</strong> 100–200 kg</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Highest extraction efficiency — maximum juice from every stalk</li>
      <li>Built-in filtration means cleaner juice with less manual work</li>
      <li>Professional appearance — ideal for branded juice bars and restaurants</li>
      <li>Safety features like auto-reverse and overload protection</li>
      <li>Suitable for very high-volume operations</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Significantly higher upfront cost (₹50,000 – ₹1,50,000+)</li>
      <li>Requires three-phase power in most cases</li>
      <li>Heavier and requires more space</li>
      <li>More complex maintenance — more components to service</li>
      <li>Spare parts can be expensive</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Ideal for:</strong> Established juice bars, restaurant chains, hotel buffet counters, food courts, and businesses focused on premium quality and hygiene.</p>

