    <h2>How to Choose the Right Sugarcane Juice Machine</h2>
    <p>Selecting the right sugarcane juice machine is not just about price — it's about matching the machine to your specific business context. Here are the key factors to evaluate:</p>

    <h3>1. Capacity (Glasses Per Hour)</h3>
    <p>This is the most important decision factor. Calculate your expected daily demand and divide by your operating hours to get your required hourly output. Then add a 25% buffer for peak hours and growth.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Small roadside stall (50–100 glasses/day):</strong> Manual or 0.5 HP electric is sufficient</li>
      <li><strong>Medium stall at a market or busy intersection (100–300 glasses/day):</strong> 1 HP or 1.5 HP electric</li>
      <li><strong>High-traffic location — mall, station, event (300–600 glasses/day):</strong> 2 HP or 3 HP electric</li>
      <li><strong>Juice bar or restaurant chain (500+ glasses/day):</strong> Automatic with filtering</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>2. Motor Power (HP)</h3>
    <p>Motor power directly affects extraction speed, juice yield, and the ability to handle thick sugarcane stalks without jamming. Here's a practical guide:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>0.5 HP:</strong> Entry-level commercial. Handles thin to medium cane. Can jam with very thick stalks. Good for starting out.</li>
      <li><strong>1 HP:</strong> The sweet spot for most commercial operations. Handles all cane sizes comfortably. Most popular choice in India.</li>
      <li><strong>1.5 HP:</strong> For busy stalls that run 8+ hours daily. More torque means less jamming and faster throughput.</li>
      <li><strong>2–3 HP:</strong> Heavy-duty commercial. For locations with very high demand or where the machine runs almost continuously.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>3. Material: SS 304 vs Regular Steel</h3>
    <p>This is a critical choice that affects hygiene, durability, and long-term cost:</p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Factor</th><th>SS 304 (Stainless Steel)</th><th>MS / Cast Iron</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Food safety</td><td>Food-grade, FSSAI compliant</td><td>Not food-grade, can rust</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Corrosion resistance</td><td>Excellent — resists sugarcane acid</td><td>Poor — rusts quickly with juice contact</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Cleaning ease</td><td>Very easy to clean and sanitize</td><td>Difficult; crevices harbour bacteria</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Durability</td><td>10–15+ years with proper care</td><td>3–5 years before rust becomes an issue</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Cost</td><td>30–50% higher upfront</td><td>Lower upfront, higher replacement cost</td></tr>
        <tr><td>FSSAI compliance</td><td>Required for licensed businesses</td><td>May not meet food safety standards</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p><strong>Our recommendation:</strong> Always go for SS 304 construction, especially for the rollers and juice contact surfaces. The extra cost pays for itself in durability, hygiene compliance, and customer trust. If budget is tight, at minimum ensure the rollers and juice tray are SS 304, even if the frame is mild steel.</p>

    <h3>4. Portability</h3>
    <p>If you operate a mobile cart or need to move the machine between locations, weight and form factor matter enormously:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Manual crushers (25–50 kg):</strong> Easily portable, can be mounted on a pushcart</li>
      <li><strong>Small electric (0.5–1 HP, 50–80 kg):</strong> Can be mounted on a wheeled cart with some effort</li>
      <li><strong>Large electric (1.5–3 HP, 80–120 kg):</strong> Semi-permanent installation recommended</li>
      <li><strong>Automatic (100–200 kg):</strong> Fixed installation only — requires a permanent counter or stand</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>5. Noise Level</h3>
    <p>If you're setting up inside a restaurant, juice bar, or mall kiosk, noise matters. Manual machines are essentially silent. Small electric motors (0.5–1 HP) produce moderate noise (60–70 dB). Larger motors (2–3 HP) can be quite loud (75–85 dB) — consider this if your setup is in an enclosed space or near customer seating. Some premium models come with noise-dampening enclosures.</p>

    <h3>6. Safety Features</h3>
    <p>Look for these safety features, especially on electric and automatic models:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Auto-reverse:</strong> Reverses roller direction if cane jams, preventing motor burnout</li>
      <li><strong>Overload protection:</strong> Cuts power if the motor is overloaded</li>
      <li><strong>Finger guard:</strong> Prevents fingers from reaching the rollers</li>
      <li><strong>Emergency stop button:</strong> Immediately halts the machine</li>
      <li><strong>Drip tray:</strong> Catches spills and keeps the floor clean</li>
    </ul>

