    <h2>Maintenance Tips for Sugarcane Juice Machines</h2>
    <p>Proper maintenance extends the life of your sugarcane machine, ensures hygiene, and prevents costly breakdowns. Here's a maintenance schedule based on machine type:</p>

    <h3>Daily Maintenance (After Every Use)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Clean all juice-contact surfaces</strong> — rollers, juice tray, filter mesh, and collection tank with hot water and food-safe detergent</li>
      <li><strong>Remove cane fibre residue</strong> — fibres stuck between rollers cause corrosion and bacterial growth</li>
      <li><strong>Wipe down the exterior</strong> — sticky juice attracts insects and causes surface corrosion</li>
      <li><strong>Drain and clean the drip tray</strong> — stagnant juice is a breeding ground for bacteria</li>
      <li><strong>Check for unusual sounds</strong> — grinding or squealing noises indicate roller misalignment or worn bearings</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Weekly Maintenance</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Lubricate gears and bearings</strong> with food-grade lubricant (not regular machine oil)</li>
      <li><strong>Check belt tension</strong> on electric models — loose belts reduce efficiency and can slip</li>
      <li><strong>Inspect rollers for wear</strong> — uneven wear patterns indicate alignment issues</li>
      <li><strong>Check electrical connections</strong> — loose wires can cause sparking or motor failure</li>
      <li><strong>Sanitize with food-grade sanitizer</strong> — especially important in hot weather</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Monthly / Quarterly Maintenance</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Professional motor servicing</strong> — check winding insulation, bearing condition, and capacitor health</li>
      <li><strong>Roller resurfacing or replacement</strong> — rollers develop smooth patches over time, reducing extraction efficiency</li>
      <li><strong>Gearbox oil change</strong> — replace gear oil every 3–6 months depending on usage intensity</li>
      <li><strong>Check and replace worn bearings</strong> — worn bearings cause vibration, noise, and eventually motor damage</li>
    </ul>

