    <h2>Hygiene & FSSAI Requirements for Sugarcane Juice Business</h2>
    <p>If you're planning to operate a commercial sugarcane juice business in India, complying with food safety regulations is not optional — it's the law. Here's what you need to know:</p>

    <h3>FSSAI Registration / License</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>FSSAI Basic Registration:</strong> For businesses with annual turnover up to ₹12 lakh. Fee: ₹100/year. This is sufficient for most sugarcane juice stalls.</li>
      <li><strong>FSSAI State License:</strong> For businesses with annual turnover between ₹12 lakh and ₹20 crore. Fee: ₹2,000–₹5,000/year. Required for larger juice bar chains.</li>
      <li><strong>Application process:</strong> Apply online at <strong>foscos.fssai.gov.in</strong>. Processing time is typically 7–60 days.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Hygiene Standards for Sugarcane Juice Vendors</h3>
    <p>FSSAI has specific guidelines for street food vendors, including sugarcane juice sellers:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Machine material:</strong> All food-contact surfaces must be food-grade stainless steel (SS 304). Cast iron rollers are technically non-compliant.</li>
      <li><strong>Water supply:</strong> Clean, potable water must be available for cleaning equipment and for adding ice (if offered)</li>
      <li><strong>Ice quality:</strong> Ice must be made from potable water. Using industrial ice is a common violation that can lead to penalties and customer illness.</li>
      <li><strong>Personal hygiene:</strong> Operators must wear clean clothing, use gloves or tongs to handle cane, and maintain basic personal hygiene</li>
      <li><strong>Waste disposal:</strong> Crushed cane bagasse must be disposed of properly — not left to accumulate around the stall</li>
      <li><strong>Pest control:</strong> The stall area should be kept clean and free from flies. Use fly nets or screens where possible.</li>
      <li><strong>Display of license:</strong> Your FSSAI registration/license number must be displayed prominently at the stall</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Tips for Maintaining Hygiene Standards</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Clean the machine after every 50–100 glasses — don't wait until end of day</li>
      <li>Use separate cutting boards and knives for trimming cane (don't place on dirty surfaces)</li>
      <li>Store sugarcane stalks off the ground on elevated racks</li>
      <li>Use disposable cups or properly washed glass tumblers (rinse with clean water between uses)</li>
      <li>Add lemon, ginger, and mint with clean utensils — not by hand</li>
      <li>Cover the juice collection container to prevent flies and dust from contaminating the juice</li>
      <li>Serve juice immediately after extraction — sugarcane juice oxidizes quickly and can harbour bacteria if left standing</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Following proper hygiene practices is equally important when setting up any food business. Check our <a href="/blog/restaurant-equipment-guide">restaurant equipment guide</a> for more on setting up a compliant commercial kitchen.</p>

