    <h2>Sugarcane Juice Machine Installation Tips</h2>
    <p>Proper installation ensures optimal performance and longevity. Here are the key considerations:</p>

    <h3>For Manual Machines</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Mount on a sturdy table or counter that can handle the weight and cranking force</li>
      <li>Bolt the machine firmly to the surface — it shouldn't move during operation</li>
      <li>Position the juice outlet over a collection container or directly over serving glasses</li>
      <li>Ensure adequate space around the machine for the operator to comfortably turn the crank</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>For Electric Machines</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Electrical supply:</strong> Ensure your power supply matches the machine's requirement (single-phase for up to 1.5 HP, three-phase for 2 HP and above)</li>
      <li><strong>Earthing:</strong> Proper electrical earthing is essential for safety — the machine operates in a wet environment with sugarcane juice splashing</li>
      <li><strong>Voltage stabilizer:</strong> In areas with voltage fluctuations, a voltage stabilizer (₹2,000–₹5,000) protects the motor from damage</li>
      <li><strong>MCB/ELCB protection:</strong> Install a miniature circuit breaker and earth leakage circuit breaker for electrical safety</li>
      <li><strong>Stable surface:</strong> Electric machines vibrate during operation — mount on a solid, level surface and use anti-vibration pads if needed</li>
      <li><strong>Drainage:</strong> Install a proper drainage system near the machine for juice overflow and wash water</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Seasonal Considerations for Sugarcane Juice Businesses</h2>
    <p>Sugarcane juice is a seasonal business in most parts of India. Understanding the seasonality helps you plan your investment and cash flow:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Peak season (March–September):</strong> High demand. Summer heat drives sales. You can sell 200–500+ glasses per day at busy locations. This is when 70–80% of your annual revenue is generated.</li>
      <li><strong>Off-season (October–February):</strong> Demand drops significantly in winter. Sales may fall to 30–80 glasses per day. Many stall owners switch to hot beverages (chai, soup) or close temporarily.</li>
      <li><strong>Sugarcane supply:</strong> Sugarcane harvesting season in India is October–March (varies by region). Ironically, this is when raw cane is cheapest, but juice demand is lowest. During peak juice season (summer), cane prices are 20–40% higher because supply is limited.</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Planning tip:</strong> If possible, negotiate a fixed-rate contract with a sugarcane supplier before summer begins. This locks in your raw material cost and protects your margins during peak season when spot prices spike. Some successful juice stall operators diversify by adding other items — fresh lime soda, coconut water, or fruit juices — to maintain revenue during the off-season.</p>

