    <h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid When Buying a Sugarcane Juice Machine</h2>
    <p>Having spoken with hundreds of juice stall operators across India, here are the most common mistakes buyers make — and how to avoid them:</p>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>Buying the cheapest machine available:</strong> A ₹12,000 cast-iron manual crusher may seem like a bargain, but if it rusts within a year and fails hygiene inspections, you'll end up spending more on replacements. Invest in SS 304 from the start.</li>
      <li><strong>Oversizing or undersizing the machine:</strong> A 3 HP machine at a stall that sells 50 glasses a day is wasted money. Conversely, a manual crusher at a busy mall location means lost revenue. Match the machine to your realistic daily volume.</li>
      <li><strong>Ignoring after-sales service:</strong> The cheapest quote is often from a manufacturer with no service network in your area. When the machine breaks down during peak season, you'll lose thousands in daily revenue waiting for parts and repairs.</li>
      <li><strong>Not checking power supply:</strong> Many buyers purchase a 2 HP three-phase machine only to discover their location only has single-phase power. Getting a three-phase connection can cost ₹10,000–₹30,000 and take weeks to arrange.</li>
      <li><strong>Skipping FSSAI registration:</strong> Operating without FSSAI registration can result in fines of ₹25,000 to ₹5,00,000. The basic registration costs just ₹100/year — there's no excuse to skip it.</li>
      <li><strong>Not testing before buying:</strong> If possible, always ask for a live demonstration with actual sugarcane before finalising the purchase. Check juice yield, noise level, and ease of feeding cane.</li>
      <li><strong>Ignoring maintenance costs:</strong> Budget for ongoing maintenance — roller replacement, belt changes, motor servicing. A machine that costs ₹35,000 upfront might cost ₹5,000–₹8,000 per year in maintenance.</li>
    </ol>

